00:57:12,862 --> 00:57:15,331
I mean, look. There's a lot of us.

763
00:57:16,165 --> 00:57:17,533
I think we're all all right.

764
00:57:19,335 --> 00:57:20,436
We are.

765
00:57:23,505 --> 00:57:24,439
Give me that.

766
00:57:30,178 --> 00:57:31,546
So long, Charlie!

767
00:57:37,017 --> 00:57:39,887
So with 2 runs in the 6th,
South Bend gets even.

768
00:57:42,789 --> 00:57:44,557
I've gotta go! I've gotta go!

769
00:57:45,525 --> 00:57:47,160
You shake it off. Shake it off.

770
00:57:50,630 --> 00:57:52,765
Say, Evelyn, can I ask you a question?

771
00:57:56,268 --> 00:57:57,503
Which team do you play for?

772
00:57:59,705 --> 00:58:01,740
- I'm a Peach.
- Well, I was just wondering...

773
00:58:02,607 --> 00:58:04,943
...because I couldn't figure out why
you'd throw home...

774
00:58:05,710 --> 00:58:07,211
...when we've got a 2-run lead!

775
00:58:07,845 --> 00:58:10,648
You let the tying run get on 2nd,
and we lost the lead!

776
00:58:11,615 --> 00:58:12,917
You start using your head!

777
00:58:13,550 --> 00:58:16,486
That's that lump that's three feet
above your ass!

778
00:58:25,128 --> 00:58:26,129
Are you crying?

779
00:58:28,164 --> 00:58:29,031
Are you crying?

780
00:58:29,498 --> 00:58:30,733
Are you crying?!

781
00:58:31,300 --> 00:58:32,668
There's no crying!

782
00:58:33,335 --> 00:58:35,037
There's no crying in baseball!

783
00:58:35,671 --> 00:58:36,905
Leave her alone, Jimmy.

784
00:58:37,506 --> 00:58:38,640
You zip it, Doris!

785
00:58:39,140 --> 00:58:42,410
Rogers Hornsby, my manager,
called me a 'talking pile of pig shit'!

786
00:58:43,411 --> 00:58:45,313
That was when my parents came
from Michigan...

787
00:58:46,080 --> 00:58:48,215
...to see me play the game!
And did I cry?

788
00:58:50,417 --> 00:58:51,518
No! Do you know why?

789
00:58:52,686 --> 00:58:55,689
Because there's no crying in baseball.
No crying in baseball!

790
00:58:56,723 --> 00:58:57,824
No crying!

791
00:58:58,391 --> 00:58:59,759
What's the matter?

792
00:59:00,360 --> 00:59:01,594
She's crying, sir.

793
00:59:02,662 --> 00:59:04,497
I didn't mean to do that.

794
00:59:05,498 --> 00:59:07,266
Perhaps you chastised her
too vehemently.

795
00:59:07,933 --> 00:59:10,802
Good rule of thumb: Treat each of them
as you would your mother.

796
00:59:13,505 --> 00:59:16,174
Anyone ever tell you you look like
a penis with a hat on?

797
00:59:17,342 --> 00:59:18,343
You're out of here!

798
00:59:18,810 --> 00:59:20,244
- I heard that!
- You misunderstood.

799
00:59:20,812 --> 00:59:22,046
- Ten seconds!
- You misunderstood!

800
00:59:22,546 --> 00:59:25,216
You can't throw me out knowing
you've got a strike!

801
00:59:26,150 --> 00:59:27,451
Off this field!

802
00:59:30,520 --> 00:59:33,056
I can't believe no one ever
called you that before!

803
00:59:33,923 --> 00:59:36,326
That's where you belong.
I'm in charge now.

804
00:59:39,262 --> 00:59:41,997
The crowd's light today,
what with the tractor show in town.

805
00:59:42,932 --> 00:59:46,768
If you're nearby, and you must be, since
this isn't a powerful radio station...

806
00:59:48,003 --> 00:59:50,539
...come on down to the ballpark
and bring the kiddies.

807
00:59:52,007 --> 00:59:53,775
People better start showing up.

808
00:59:54,409 --> 00:59:56,310
We don't have fans,
we don't have a league.

809
00:59:57,044 --> 00:59:58,279
Ladies...

810
00:59:59,380 --> 01:00:00,748
...you all look wonderful.

811
01:00:03,050 --> 01:00:07,154
There's a reporter and a photographer
in the stands from Life magazine.

812
01:00:08,555 --> 01:00:10,123
- We're famous!
- Life magazine?

813
01:00:10,724 --> 01:00:12,225
Don't waste your time.

814
01:00:14,260 --> 01:00:16,929
Dottie, I'm trying to get them to do
a story about you.

815
01:00:17,897 --> 01:00:19,331
Me? Why me?

816
01:00:20,132 --> 01:00:22,501
You're the "Queen of Diamonds."
That's what I'm calling you.

817
01:00:24,303 --> 01:00:25,670
Did you tell them about me?

818
01:00:26,271 --> 01:00:28,807
I told them how at first,
the scout didn't even want you...

819
01:00:29,741 --> 01:00:32,143
...but how Dottie wouldn't come
without her kid sister.

820
01:00:33,644 --> 01:00:35,146
They really loved it.

821
01:00:37,081 --> 01:00:38,849
A real human-interest story.

822
01:00:40,951 --> 01:00:44,254
Will you just try to give them
something spectacular out there?

823
01:00:45,355 --> 01:00:46,222
Anything.

824
01:00:46,623 --> 01:00:47,624
What's the matter?

825
01:00:50,259 --> 01:00:52,028
Well, we're not doing so well.

826
01:00:53,095 --> 01:00:56,031
Harvey and the other owners think
they've made a mistake.

827
01:00:57,132 --> 01:00:58,367
They might close you down.

828
01:00:59,968 --> 01:01:01,603
What are you talking about?

829
01:01:02,270 --> 01:01:03,838
They can't close us down here.

830
01:01:04,439 --> 01:01:06,574
- What kind of a thing is that?
- What's it mean?

831
01:01:07,308 --> 01:01:10,111
They're businessmen.
No profit, no product.

832
01:01:11,045 --> 01:01:12,613
And what am I supposed to do?

833
01:01:13,214 --> 01:01:14,915
Go back to taxi dancing?

834
01:01:15,582 --> 01:01:18,385
Ten cents so some slob can sweat
gin all over me?

835
01:01:19,953 --> 01:01:21,388
I'm never doing that again!

836
01:01:22,055 --> 01:01:26,025
So you tell old rich Mr. Chocolate Man
that he ain't closing me down!

837
01:01:27,293 --> 01:01:28,861
They can't keep us from playing!

838
01:01:29,462 --> 01:01:31,030
We'll show them how we play.

839
01:01:32,398 --> 01:01:35,634
I'm sorry. I'm very sorry.
I am trying my best.

840
01:01:36,969 --> 01:01:39,571
So will you just give them
everything you've got?

841
01:01:40,438 --> 01:01:41,706
We always do.

842
01:01:46,677 --> 01:01:49,213
A slick play by Alice Gaspers
and there's 2 gone...

843
01:01:50,114 --> 01:01:52,249
...in the 3rd.
That'll bring up Dee Lynch.

844
01:01:55,819 --> 01:01:58,755
Lynch is the most consistent
Belles hitter this year.

845
01:02:00,356 --> 01:02:01,658
Settles in.

846
01:02:04,193 --> 01:02:05,695
Pops it up! Foul.

847
01:02:06,329 --> 01:02:08,097
Hinson should have
no trouble with this.

848
01:02:08,764 --> 01:02:09,565
She's under it.

849
01:02:10,933 --> 01:02:12,034
Uncle Elmore's socks!

850
01:02:12,501 --> 01:02:14,269
What did she do?

851
01:02:17,772 --> 01:02:18,873
I can't do that.

852
01:02:19,407 --> 01:02:20,208
Who can?

853
01:02:20,642 --> 01:02:23,177
- What is her name?
- Dottie Hinson. D-O-T-T-I-E...

854
01:02:24,979 --> 01:02:26,347
What the hell was that?

855
01:02:26,947 --> 01:02:28,849
I just thought it might
help the league.

856
01:02:29,616 --> 01:02:31,451
A goddamn circus!

857
01:02:32,119 --> 01:02:33,553
A double would be nice-

858
01:02:34,154 --> 01:02:35,455
All right!

859
01:02:36,856 --> 01:02:38,424
God knows we have a game.

860
01:02:40,259 --> 01:02:42,528
It's not like any of this helps,
believe me.

861
01:02:54,305 --> 01:02:55,240
That was really nice!

862
01:02:55,673 --> 01:02:59,510
Let's go, girls. Dozens of people are
waiting for the game to start.

863
01:03:27,636 --> 01:03:28,303
Batter!

864
01:03:31,840 --> 01:03:33,808
What is her name?
Hey you, tall girl!

865
01:03:34,542 --> 01:03:35,343
Beverly!

866
01:03:35,810 --> 01:03:37,712
Look sharp, tall-
What is her name?

867
01:03:38,379 --> 01:03:39,680
Beverly. Good.

868
01:03:44,484 --> 01:03:45,852
Five bucks! Five bucks!

869
01:03:51,991 --> 01:03:55,294
What if, at a key moment in the game,
my uniform bursts open...

870
01:03:56,495 --> 01:03:57,863
...and my bosoms fly out?

871
01:03:58,497 --> 01:04:00,699
That might draw a crowd, right?

872
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:03,969
Think there's men
who ain't seen your bosoms?

873
01:04:04,703 --> 01:04:05,804
Thank you.

874
01:04:07,005 --> 01:04:08,973
- Marla, what you got?
- What about me?

875
01:04:09,707 --> 01:04:11,476
I got a letter from Nelson!

876
01:04:15,045 --> 01:04:16,680
Fly ball as Dottie Hinson brings...

877
01:04:17,314 --> 01:04:19,149
...the crowd to its feet
with a home run!

878
01:04:22,519 --> 01:04:23,453
22!

879
01:04:29,492 --> 01:04:31,127
We love you, 22!

880
01:04:31,761 --> 01:04:33,529
- Come on!
- Open your mouth!

881
01:04:35,331 --> 01:04:36,498
The kid ate the lineup!

882
01:04:39,434 --> 01:04:40,102
Right here.

883
01:04:58,418 --> 01:05:00,387
I'm so happy! Thank you.

884
01:05:06,192 --> 01:05:06,993
I love you.

885
01:05:08,594 --> 01:05:09,962
I'll be back next season.

886
01:05:10,563 --> 01:05:11,997
See you next season!

887
01:05:18,870 --> 01:05:20,371
Slide! Slide!

888
01:05:21,406 --> 01:05:22,206
Safe!

889
01:05:22,774 --> 01:05:23,574
Thank you!

890
01:05:24,041 --> 01:05:25,276
Let it up. Let it up.

891
01:05:27,711 --> 01:05:28,712
That was a good one.

892
01:05:30,180 --> 01:05:31,482
It's a fly ball to left!

893
01:05:32,849 --> 01:05:35,185
Betty Spaghetti makes the catch!

894
01:05:36,353 --> 01:05:39,088
Heads up! Spaghetti makes the throw!
It's gonna be close!

895
01:05:41,858 --> 01:05:43,826
Aunt Edna's bridgework! She is out!

896
01:05:44,560 --> 01:05:46,896
Dottie Hinson held onto the ball!

897
01:05:47,730 --> 01:05:49,031
Oh, doctor!

898
01:05:52,234 --> 01:05:53,735
A lot of ballplayers use it.

899
01:06:07,648 --> 01:06:08,949
High foul pop.

900
01:06:09,583 --> 01:06:10,584
It's coming back!

901
01:06:12,953 --> 01:06:14,521
She caught it! Unbelievable!

902
01:06:15,221 --> 01:06:18,357
Full house on its feet
cheering Dottie Hinson!

903
01:06:24,596 --> 01:06:25,898
That sounded good.

904
01:06:26,665 --> 01:06:28,800
- You haven't got a curve ball left.
- I don't?!

905
01:06:29,568 --> 01:06:30,936
You haven't had one since-

906
01:06:57,159 --> 01:06:58,160
Safe!

907
01:06:59,094 --> 01:06:59,828
Safe!

908
01:07:31,157 --> 01:07:31,958
He's good-looking.

909
01:07:33,793 --> 01:07:36,462
- What's he do when not in the Army?
- Dairy assistant manager.

910
01:07:37,363 --> 01:07:38,730
He'll be manager. He's smart.

911
01:07:40,265 --> 01:07:42,100
So he's good-looking and smart.

912
01:07:42,834 --> 01:07:44,135
There's so few of us.

913
01:07:46,204 --> 01:07:47,972
Where did you say he was? Italy?

914
01:07:48,639 --> 01:07:51,776
I think. I haven't got a letter
from him in three weeks.

915
01:07:52,810 --> 01:07:54,245
I used to get one every week.

916
01:07:56,413 --> 01:07:57,981
That doesn't mean anything.

917
01:07:59,649 --> 01:08:03,286
If he's in combat, it's not like there's
a mailbox on every corner.

918
01:08:04,921 --> 01:08:07,523
If something happened,
you would've got a telegram.

919
01:08:08,457 --> 01:08:09,191
Oh, God, don't-

920
01:08:09,625 --> 01:08:11,961
But he's fine. No, he's fine.

921
01:08:15,797 --> 01:08:17,232
How come you're not in the Army?

922
01:08:19,467 --> 01:08:20,468
I have no cartilage...

923
01:08:21,503 --> 01:08:22,570
...in my knee.

924
01:08:23,037 --> 01:08:24,605
You don't need it to shoot Nazis.

925
01:08:25,206 --> 01:08:27,942
You need this, right? Trigger finger.
I could do that.

926
01:08:33,380 --> 01:08:35,415
How did I get so useless so fast?

927
01:08:41,020 --> 01:08:42,655
Boys like this on your fingers?

928
01:08:43,289 --> 01:08:44,357
Works for me.

929
01:08:48,060 --> 01:08:49,695
Your sister's not gonna be mad?

930
01:08:50,362 --> 01:08:51,597
I don't care.

931
01:08:53,298 --> 01:08:54,466
Listen, when...

932
01:08:55,634 --> 01:08:57,268
- Bob.
- ... Bob comes back...

933
01:08:58,536 --> 01:08:59,971
...will you keep playing?

934
01:09:02,039 --> 01:09:03,040
You could just quit?

935
01:09:03,507 --> 01:09:04,442
Sure.

936
01:09:05,342 --> 01:09:06,477
You play like you love it.

937
01:09:11,148 --> 01:09:13,116
- Does he know how good you are?
- Bob?

938
01:09:13,850 --> 01:09:15,218
No, Hitler. Yes, Bob.

939
01:09:16,419 --> 01:09:17,420
How good am I?

940
01:09:21,424 --> 01:09:22,591
You stink.

941
01:09:23,559 --> 01:09:24,693
You're lousy.

942
01:09:25,894 --> 01:09:29,298
You're only the best player
in the league. You don't know that?

943
01:09:32,534 --> 01:09:33,768
You ever been married?

944
01:09:36,371 --> 01:09:37,872
Let me think. Yeah, twice.

945
01:09:39,340 --> 01:09:40,007
Any children?

946
01:09:41,242 --> 01:09:42,510
One of them was.

947
01:09:45,712 --> 01:09:47,147
Is she out?

948
01:09:48,749 --> 01:09:50,717
I think it's time for a drink.

949
01:09:52,318 --> 01:09:53,953
Hang on. Hang on.

950
01:09:56,689 --> 01:09:58,124
These really don't mix.

951
01:10:12,403 --> 01:10:14,439
- Good, huh?
- Oh, yeah. It's great.

952
01:10:21,612 --> 01:10:22,546
Fair ball!

953
01:10:30,720 --> 01:10:31,454
Time!

954
01:10:31,888 --> 01:10:34,023
Jimmy Dugan pops his head
out of the dugout.

955
01:10:34,757 --> 01:10:36,926
He's on his way to talk to his hurler.

956
01:10:38,227 --> 01:10:40,329
Kit Keller looks mighty tired.

957
01:10:42,097 --> 01:10:43,398
Game's getting exciting.

958
01:10:45,300 --> 01:10:46,601
I'll finish it right here.

959
01:10:47,135 --> 01:10:48,569
I'll strike this turkey out.

960
01:10:50,104 --> 01:10:51,472
Betty's ready to come in.

961
01:10:52,073 --> 01:10:54,041
Come on. I've never been
taken out before.

962
01:10:54,875 --> 01:10:55,542
Ask Dottie.

963
01:10:56,877 --> 01:10:58,579
I really wanna finish this game.

964
01:10:59,613 --> 01:11:00,480
Please?

965
01:11:04,084 --> 01:11:04,818
What do you think?

966
01:11:06,719 --> 01:11:09,188
Well, you know, she's battling.

967
01:11:11,057 --> 01:11:11,991
What do you think?

968
01:11:14,193 --> 01:11:15,627
She's throwing grapefruits.

969
01:11:20,131 --> 01:11:23,902
It looks like Keller's coming out of
the game, and she is not happy about it!

970
01:11:25,370 --> 01:11:26,938
Nice job, Kit!

971
01:11:28,039 --> 01:11:31,108
Betty Horn sprints in
from the left-field bullpen.

972
01:11:33,977 --> 01:11:37,047
Look at this crowd. This is great!
They're jumping, cheering...

973
01:11:38,081 --> 01:11:39,349
...and they paid to get in.

974
01:11:39,883 --> 01:11:42,085
You did a fabulous job.
I won't forget this.

975
01:11:42,885 --> 01:11:46,122
Thank you very much, Mr. Harvey.
I appreciate it, coming from you.

976
01:11:47,323 --> 01:11:50,826
But to be perfectly honest, I think
the girls deserve most of the credit.

977
01:11:51,994 --> 01:11:52,794
They're great.

978
01:11:53,228 --> 01:11:56,031
Fortunately, we won't need
them anymore. Do you want a peanut?

979
01:11:56,965 --> 01:11:58,266
No. What do you mean?

980
01:11:59,767 --> 01:12:01,069
What do I mean?

981
01:12:01,636 --> 01:12:04,105
We're winning the war.
Our situation changed.

982
01:12:04,939 --> 01:12:08,375
Roosevelt himself said,
"Men's baseball won't be shut down."

983
01:12:09,443 --> 01:12:11,478
So we won't need the girls next year.

984
01:12:14,748 --> 01:12:17,750
Bases loaded. Bottom of the 9th.
Rockford up, 6 to 2. Two men out.

985
01:12:18,718 --> 01:12:20,553
No balls, 2 strikes.

986
01:12:22,088 --> 01:12:23,789
Strike 3!

987
01:12:25,291 --> 01:12:28,660
And that is the ball game!
Rockford is in the playoffs!

988
01:12:32,230 --> 01:12:35,033
I love these girls.
I don't need them, but I love them.

989
01:12:35,934 --> 01:12:37,035
Come on. Let's go.

990
01:12:38,569 --> 01:12:40,771
Look at me. I'm full of peanuts!

991
01:12:41,572 --> 01:12:43,474
I've got peanuts all over myself.

992
01:12:44,141 --> 01:12:46,610
This is what it's gonna be like
in the factories too.

993
01:12:48,078 --> 01:12:49,713
"Men are back.
Turn in your rivets."

994
01:12:50,847 --> 01:12:53,583
First, it was their patriotic duty
to get out and go to work.

995
01:12:54,484 --> 01:12:56,953
When the men come back,
they're sent back to the kitchen.

996
01:12:58,588 --> 01:13:02,291
Should we send the boys returning
from war back to the kitchen? Come on.

997
01:13:06,194 --> 01:13:08,864
Do you know how dedicated they are?
What they go through?

998
01:13:09,798 --> 01:13:11,966
They play with sprained ankles,
broken fingers.

999
01:13:12,700 --> 01:13:15,436
They ride a bus all night to play
a double-header the next day!

1000
01:13:16,871 --> 01:13:18,305
I'll make it up to them.

1001
01:13:18,939 --> 01:13:20,140
What? With Harvey Bars?

1002
01:13:20,641 --> 01:13:22,776
I'm getting tired of listening
to you, Ira.

1003
01:13:25,345 --> 01:13:28,014
I'd like your permission
to take over the league.

1004
01:13:30,049 --> 01:13:32,251
Do you understand?
All of the owners are getting out.

1005
01:13:33,052 --> 01:13:34,687
There's no point to it anymore.

1006
01:13:35,321 --> 01:13:37,590
Just let them finish the season,
and that's it!

1007
01:13:38,357 --> 01:13:41,727
I sold your product when there was
no product. This is a product!

1008
01:13:43,962 --> 01:13:46,765
There is no room for girls' baseball
in this country...

1009
01:13:47,665 --> 01:13:49,434
...once the war is over.

1010
01:13:50,535 --> 01:13:51,269
They're through.

1011
01:13:52,803 --> 01:13:54,238
I think you're wrong.

1012
01:13:55,506 --> 01:13:57,775
And I'm gonna prove it to you,
Mr. Harvey!

1013
01:13:59,343 --> 01:14:02,546
Hi, my name's Mae. That's more
than a name, that's an attitude.

1014
01:14:04,014 --> 01:14:07,016
Here's my friend Doris.
